<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06195068 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06195068 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Williams  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  US; MILITARY; PLANNING; IRAQ  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Bush administration sternly warned Iraq on Friday of its willingness touse a new border strike force if the Iraqi government resumes attacks on Kurdsor engages in other aggressive conduct after the United States pulls itstroops out of the country Monday.;    The United States and its coalitionpartners, who are turning military security over to a multinational forcebased in neighboring Turkey, have &quot;laid down a marker&quot; with Iraq, Pentagonspokesman Pete Williams told reporters.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  U.S. WARNS IRAQ IT'S ALERT FOR AGGRESSION  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Mercury News wire services contributed to this report.  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;We have made it clear to Iraq that we maintain the capability and thewillingness to undertake future action and further action if necessary,&quot;Williams declared. &quot;The coalition retains a clear interest in peace withinIraq and is willing to respond militarily to Iraqi actions that disturb thepeace.&quot;;    U.N. demands; In a similar warning Friday, the United Nations'five permanent Security Council members told Iraq's U.N. ambassador that hisgovernment must swiftly disclose its nuclear program or face seriousconsequences, U.N. diplomats said.;    Western diplomats declined to call itan ultimatum, but said the warning was strong and unmistakable and thatimmediate cooperation was necessary.;    Pentagon spokesman Williams said theUnited States and its allies will act to prevent Iraq from flying planes orhelicopters over the northern portion of the country above the 36th parallel.;   He also cautioned that Iraqi troops, police and border patrols must keepout of the smaller security zone north of the 36th parallel that was earlierset aside for the security of the Kurds. And he warned that Iraq must notinterfere in any way with continuing relief efforts for the Kurds.;    Strikeplans;  Pentagon officials confirmed Friday that the administration had drawnup contingency plans for air strikes on a number of targets inside Iraq.Williams declined to discuss those targets, other than to suggest that suchtargets would be military rather than civilian or industrial.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Los Angeles Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910713  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  15A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  323  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday July 13, 199100195068,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>